ce:section.ce:para:
This paper reviews the application of nanomaterials-based fluorescent assays for the detection of pathogenic bacteria in the food-related matrices (Fig. 1
                      & Table 1
                     ). Firstly, it mainly classifies the recognition methods of nanomaterials and targets, including specific recognition methods based on antibodies, enzymes, aptamers, whole cells, phages and antibiotics, and some non-specific recognition methods based on the nature of bacteria themselves or other principles. Secondly, different unique nanoparticles for pathogenic bacteria detection are reported, mainly gold nanomaterials, silver nanomaterials, quantum dots, UCNPs, magnetic nanomaterials, carbon nanomaterials and metal-organic frameworks/covalent organic frameworks. On top of that, the application prospects and development directions of nanomaterials-based fluorescent assays in pathogenic bacterial detection are initially foreseen. Although many studies to date have focused on a review of the detection of pathogenic bacteria in the food, to our knowledge, few applications of nanomaterials-based fluorescent assays for the detection of pathogenic bacteria in the food-related matrices have been systematically reported (Bhardwaj, et al., 2021; Nnachi et al., 2022). In view of this, the aim of this paper is to discuss in depth the research progress of nanomaterials-based fluorescent assays for stable, rapid, sensitive and selective detection of various pathogenic bacteria in the food, with the aim of providing a more efficient, accurate, reliable, economical, environmentally friendly and commercialized detection method. Finally, to maintain food and human safety.
